                            <comment id="17600118" author="paulk" created="Sun, 4 Sep 2022 23:00:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;You need to delete the slf4j-api-1.7.32.jar in your Groovy install&apos;s lib directory since you can&apos;t mix slf4j 1.x and 2.x. That jar is in the standard distribution to support TestNG, so if you delete it, you will need to add some @Grab statements to any TestNG tests that you want to run in the Groovy console.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Alternatively, you can use a Maven/Gradle build for your project and ensure that old slf4j dependencies aren&apos;t included.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We should probably look at bumping the TestNG slf4j dependency to 2.0 since that seems to cause less problems even with 1.x slf dependencies explicitly added.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17600119" author="rvenk" created="Sun, 4 Sep 2022 23:12:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thank you. That seems be a good workaround my tests pass. However, as you pointed out upgrading the slf4j dependency to 2.0 would be a good permanent fix.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17600721" author="paulk" created="Tue, 6 Sep 2022 10:40:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This should be fixed in the next release. Thanks for spotting the issue.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
